text: michael phelps moved closer to mark
spitz on friday winning the 200-meter
individual medley in a world record
it was his sixth gold and sixth world
record in his many races the event which
consists of a lap each of the four
strokes provides the perfect canvas for
his exquisite technique the individual
medal he begins with the butterfly which
was the stroke that Phelps first
qualified for at the Olympics in 2000
Phelps has two strong kicks on each
stroke one when his arms are in front of
him and the other when his hands are
sweeping past his hips
Phelps like spits breathes on every
stroke as opposed to every other as most
swimmers do without his speed being at
all diminished this is very hard to do
Phelps was on world-record pace after
the butterfly leg and he touched the
wall after the backstroke still in first
still ahead of the record the third leg
of breaststroke Phelps increased his
lead as if he had forgotten it was his
weakest stroke the breast of freestyle
turn highlighted another of Phelps's
strengths his underwater dolphin kick
after pushing off the wall the dolphin
kick is a whip like motion that starts
at the upper body and snaps out of the
toes to do it well you need good breath
control strong legs and flexible joints
and Phelps has all of these this is
Karin Krause of the New York Times
reporting from Beijing
